      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical used under documented QMS with version control and regression testing suite. FDA in-house FEA code validated per ISO 9001 procedures.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) are operated under formal software quality management systems with documented version control, change control, and regression test suites. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2 for medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions solved; patch tests and single-element tests passed for all element types used.",
      "rationale": "Benchmark verification problems including Timoshenko beam bending and Hertzian contact were solved by each code. All codes reproduced analytical solutions within 0.5% for the element types employed in the pedicle screw model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study conducted; QoI change <2% between penultimate and final mesh density.",
      "rationale": "A four-level mesh refinement study was performed on the pedicle screw–rod–vertebral block assembly. Von Mises stress at the screw root and construct stiffness both converged to within 1.3% between the two finest mesh densities. Final mesh density selected for all production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals below 1e-6; direct solver used for contact-dominated steps with verified pivot tolerance.",
      "rationale": "Static nonlinear analyses used Newton–Raphson iteration with force and displacement residual tolerances of 1e-6. Contact steps used a direct sparse solver. Energy balance checked at each load increment; no spurious energy detected."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments prior to production runs.",
      "rationale": "Model setup (geometry import, material card assignment, boundary condition application, contact pair definitions) reviewed by a second analyst not involved in model construction. Discrepancies resolved before production simulation runs. Documented in internal review record NR-2023-047."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with nonlinear geometry and frictional contact judged appropriate for construct-level stiffness and yield force prediction under quasi-static loading.",
      "rationale": "The continuum FEA representation captures the dominant load-transfer mechanisms (screw–rod interface friction, screw shank bending, block compliance) relevant to ASTM F1717 compression-bending. Nonlinear geometry activated to capture large-displacement effects at 40 mm displacement endpoint. Bilinear isotropic hardening material model for Ti-6Al-4V validated against coupon data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (E, yield stress, UTS, hardening slope) sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V rod and screw material properties measured from lot-specific tensile coupons (n=5 per lot). UHMWPE block elastic modulus from compression testing per ASTM D695. Screw and rod geometry digitized via CMM to ±0.005 mm. Friction coefficient at screw–rod interface determined from dedicated tribology tests (μ = 0.18 ± 0.02)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs; specimens drawn from production lots; dimensional inspection confirms within engineering drawing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-representative hardware. All specimens dimensionally inspected by CMM prior to testing. Specimens span two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes R&D), providing inter-laboratory reproducibility data. Sample size exceeds minimum required for medium decision consequence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate COU loading environment; multiple load levels or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed strictly per ASTM F1717 protocol (single compression-bending configuration, single load rate). Only one test condition (static, room temperature) was evaluated; cyclic fatigue and elevated-temperature conditions were not included. Achieved level 2 is below the required level 3 for this factor; this gap is acknowledged in the overall credibility assessment and accepted given the scope limitation to static performance claims only."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters (geometry, material, BCs, torque preload) demonstrably equivalent to test specimen parameters within stated uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "One-to-one correspondence established between FEA model inputs and measured specimen parameters for each of the 11 constructs. Screw insertion torque (4 Nm) applied in FEA via bolt-pretension element matching measured torque wrench values (4.0 ± 0.1 Nm). Material properties from same production lot as test specimens."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 and relative QoI difference <10% for all three QoIs.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy both acceptance criteria. E/uval values: 0.91 (stiffness), 1.14 (yield force), 1.73 (force at 40 mm). Relative errors: 4.7%, 6.2%, 8.9% respectively. Validation uncertainty uval computed per ASME V&V 20-2009 combining experimental repeatability, inter-laboratory bias, and model numerical uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly map to regulatory submission requirements and clinical failure modes of interest (construct stiffness, structural yield, large-displacement load-bearing).",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the spine and is a primary regulatory QoI. Yield force and force at 40 mm displacement are standard ASTM F1717 acceptance metrics directly referenced in 510(k) substantial equivalence determinations. All three QoIs are mechanistically linked to the primary failure mode (fatigue crack initiation at screw root under cyclic bending)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity geometry, loading, and boundary conditions are sufficiently representative of the COU to support extrapolation of credibility to the intended prediction.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical 7.5 mm non-cannulated screw geometry, rod diameter, and UHMWPE block fixture as specified in the COU. ASTM F1717 compression-bending is the standard surrogate for in vivo posterior spinal fixation loading. The validation constructs are drawn from the same production design as the COU device, supporting direct applicability of the credibility evidence."
    }
